Compare baseline characteristics

scale_names <- c("age" = "Age",
                 "gender" = "Gender: Male",
                 "ms" = "Prior growth mindset",
                 "cams" = "Trait mindfulness",
                 "risc" = "Ego-resilience",
                 "grit" = "Grit",
                 "sc" = "Self-compassion",
                 "se" = "Global self-esteem")

processed_final %>%
  select(
    mindset, intervention,
    gender, age, 
    ms_mean, cams_mean, risc_mean, grit_mean, sc_mean, se_mean) %>%
  mutate(gender = recode(gender, `Female` = 0L, `Male` = 1L)) %>% 
  group_by(mindset, intervention) %>%
  summarise(across(gender:se_mean, 
                   list("Mean" = mean, "SD" = sd), na.rm = TRUE), 
            .groups = "drop") %>% 
  pivot_longer(-c("mindset", "intervention")) %>% 
  mutate(name = str_remove(name, "_mean")) %>% 
  separate(name, into = c("Measure", "stat")) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "stat", values_from = "value") %>% 
  mutate(Measure = recode(Measure, !!!scale_names)) %>% 
  unite("group", c("mindset", "intervention"), sep = "-") %>% 
  mutate(across(c(Mean, SD), ~round(.x, 2) %>% 
                              format(nsmall = 2))) %>% 
  unite("mn", c("Mean", "SD"), sep = " (") %>% 
  mutate(mn = paste0(mn, ")")) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = "group", values_from = "mn") %>% 
  mutate(across(-Measure, ~if_else(Measure == "Gender: Male", 
                                    str_remove(.x, "\\(.*\\)") %>% 
                                     parse_number() %>% 
                                     percent(accuracy = .1),
                                    .x) %>% 
                           str_squish())) %>% 
  gt() %>% 
  tab_spanner(label = "Group",
              columns = `Fixed-Control`:`Growth-Mindfulness`) %>% 
  tab_options(row.striping.include_table_body = TRUE,
              row.striping.background_color = "#EEEEEE", 
              row.striping.include_stub = TRUE,
              column_labels.background.color = "#CCCCCC",
              column_labels.font.weight = "bold" 
              )

Manipulation check

The manipulation for mindset was successful, as those in the fixed mindset group had a stronger belief that intelligence cannot be changed over time. On the other hand, the mindfulness induction did not make the participants more mindful.

Mindset manipulation check

report(lm(mc_3 ~ mindset + ms_mean, data = processed_final))
## We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict mc_3 with mindset and ms_mean (formula: mc_3 ~ mindset + ms_mean). The model explains a statistically significant and substantial proportion of variance (R2 = 0.50, F(2, 380) = 190.60, p < .001, adj. R2 = 0.50). The model's intercept, corresponding to mindset = Fixed and ms_mean = 0, is at 6.64 (95% CI [6.27, 7.01], t(380) = 35.39, p < .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of mindset [Growth] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -0.77, 95% CI [-0.95, -0.59], t(380) = -8.36, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.61, 95% CI [-0.75, -0.46])
##   - The effect of ms_mean is statistically significant and negative (beta = -0.77, 95% CI [-0.85, -0.68], t(380) = -17.21, p < .001; Std. beta = -0.62, 95% CI [-0.70, -0.55])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset.

Mindfulness induction manipulation check

report(lm(mc_1 ~ intervention + cams_mean, data = processed_final))
## We fitted a linear model (estimated using OLS) to predict mc_1 with intervention and cams_mean (formula: mc_1 ~ intervention + cams_mean). The model explains a statistically significant and weak proportion of variance (R2 = 0.03, F(2, 380) = 6.63, p = 0.001, adj. R2 = 0.03). The model's intercept, corresponding to intervention = Control and cams_mean = 0, is at 1.72 (95% CI [0.78, 2.66], t(380) = 3.59, p < .001). Within this model:
## 
##   - The effect of intervention [Mindfulness] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.07, 95% CI [-0.33, 0.20], t(380) = -0.48, p = 0.629; Std. beta = -0.05, 95% CI [-0.25, 0.15])
##   - The effect of cams_mean is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.60, 95% CI [0.27, 0.93], t(380) = 3.60, p < .001; Std. beta = 0.18, 95% CI [0.08, 0.28])
## 
## Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset.

Dispositional confounders of the manipulation

Dispositional mindset

Those with higher dispositional growth mindset and / or mindfulness were less likely to believe that intelligence cannot be changed over time.

processed_final %>% 
  select(mc_1, mc_3, cams_mean, ms_mean) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(y = mc_3, x = ms_mean) +
  geom_point(alpha = .1) +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  labs(x = "Dispositional growth mindset", y = "Statement: \"Your intelligence is an attribute that you cannot change over time\"")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Dispositional mindfulness

Similarly, those with dispositional mindfulness were more likely to be able to get into a calm and focused state.

  select(mc_1, mc_3, cams_mean, ms_mean) %>%

Test main outcomes

Number of solved optional exercises

We test the main hypothesis, that is the association of the mindset (fixed vs.growth) and mindfulness induction (mindfulness vs.control) with the number of solved optional exercises.

mod_1 <- glm(extra_tasks ~ mindset * intervention, 
           family = "poisson", 
           data = processed_final)

mod_2 <- glm(extra_tasks ~ mindset + intervention, 
             family = "poisson",
             data = processed_final)

tab_model(mod_1, mod_2, 
          dv.labels = c("Interaction", "Only main effects"),
          show.aic = TRUE, 
          show.stat = TRUE, 
          p.style = "numeric", 
          show.loglik = TRUE, 
          show.dev = TRUE, 
          show.zeroinf = TRUE)

The tests show both overdispersion and zero-inflation, therefore we need to use a model that corrects for these.
